item.title: Japanese trains are neat…
item.description: Apparently Japanese high speed trains are blasted with water as the spray reduces aerodynamic pressure on the body and helps the train cut through the air more smoothly. The water also cools the brakes, traps dust kicked up at high speeds, and dampens noise that would otherwise spike as the train enters tunnels or crosses pressure zones. Thought this was neat & wanted to share! Have a great day on Imgur & Love from Japan!

item.title: The disgusting full story behind dual citizenship
item.description: When you become a US citizen (as I did in 2019) you swear to end all allegiance to any foreign country. Since 1967 (as decided in Afroyim v. Rusk, but in common practice long before then) this does not end your citizenship of another country. If the other country allows dual citizenship you become a dual citizen. Similarly if you qualify for citizenship abroad through a parent. This has been upheld by the Supreme Court. So (almost) every US citizen not born here (and some who are) are are dual citizens, even if like me they have no intention or interest in ever returning to their former country. Usually dual citizenship can only be ended through a long formal process which for many means traveling back to those countries or traveling to an embassy. If they make dual citizenship illegal it doesn't actually end that dual citizenship, that requires the formal process of renounciation. All such a law would do is turn 25 MILLION citizens into criminals. And what do we do with criminal immigrants? Well, you know. You know because they are saying it out loud what their plans are. Their plans were laid out plainly in Project 2025 This push to end dual citizenship is a smokescreen to delegitimize the naturalization of US citizens. A legal pretence to round up and imprison/disappear/deport US citizens. ICE knows where we live, where we work, who our relatives are, because that's part of the immigration process - USCIS/BorderPatrol/ICE has all those details on file. CALL YOUR REPRESENTATIVE NOW http://www.house.gov/representatives/find-your-representative
